    <p>You don’t need a green thumb to grow these plants in your bal­cony or cor­ri­dor.</p>
    <p>With more ur­ban dwellers working from home, there has been a surge in the num­ber of home­own­ers tak­ing up gardening and ur­ban farm­ing as a hobby.</p>
    <p>Cul­ti­vat­ing dec­o­ra­tive plants brighten up your space, while grow­ing herbs and veg­eta­bles is a con­ve­nient way to en­joy or­ganic pro­duce.</p>
    <p>With their pink and pur­ple  ow­ers, African vi­o­lets are an at­trac­tive and low-main­te­nance house­plant. They grow best in bright but in­di­rect light.</p>
    <p>P E A C E L I LY</p>
    <p>These trop­i­cal peren­ni­als beau­tify the home and o  ce with their grace­ful  ow­ers. They do best in shaded ar­eas with some in­di­rect light, and re­quire wa­ter­ing about once a week.</p>
    <p>Pars­ley doesn’t re­quire a lot of</p>
    <p>CAIXIN</p>
    <p>Needs a bright and airy space,</p>
    <p>with good air  ow and rich soil.</p>
    <p>You can har­vest this af­ter 30  0 days.</p>
    <p>KALE</p>
    <p>Needs bright sun­light but a cool en­vi­ron­ment. Kale also can­not be in soil that’s too wet or wa­ter­logged, so make sure you grow it in well-drained soil.</p>
    <p>HEARTLEAF PHILO­DEN­DRON</p>
    <p>The heartleaf philo­den­dron does  ne in low light con­di­tions. The soil should be kept evenly moist, not too wet or dry.</p>

